<h2>Step-by-Step Nostrifizierung Process</h2>
<h3>Step 1: Choose a University</h3>
<p>Submit your application to one of Austria's three medical universities:</p>
<ul><li><strong>Medizinische Universität Wien</strong> — Largest, most applications</li><li><strong>Medizinische Universität Graz</strong> — Smaller, potentially faster processing</li><li><strong>Medizinische Universität Innsbruck</strong> — Located in Tyrol, scenic Alpine setting</li></ul>

<h3>Step 2: Submit Required Documents</h3>
<ul><li>Medical degree diploma (apostilled and translated by a sworn translator)</li><li>Detailed academic transcript with subject hours</li><li>Curriculum/study plan from your university</li><li>Certificate of good standing</li><li>Passport copy</li></ul>

<h3>Step 3: Curriculum Comparison</h3>
<p>The university compares your curriculum with the Austrian medical curriculum. Gaps in training are identified as <strong>Ergänzungsprüfungen</strong> (supplementary exams) that must be passed.</p>

<h3>Step 4: Pass Required Exams</h3>
<p>Common subjects for Ergänzungsprüfungen include pharmacology, pathology, and Austrian healthcare law. You have 3 attempts per exam.</p>

<h3>Step 5: Register with Ärztekammer</h3>
<p>After receiving the Nostrifizierungsbescheid, register with the Austrian Medical Chamber to obtain your <strong>ius practicandi</strong> (right to practice).</p>

